      "prompt": "Your tomatoes have yellowing leaves and stunted growth in the first month of summer, but you haven't repotted yet or changed fertilizer since spring started.\n\nBased on standard soil nutrient cycles for potted plants:\n1. Identify the most likely missing primary macronutrient causing these specific symptoms.\n2. Name one common organic amendment that naturally replenishes this nutrient without requiring a full chemical synthesis step, and explain briefly how it contributes to plant health in containers.",
      "answer": "Nitrogen (N). Compost or well-rotted manure are suitable amendments. They slowly release nitrogen into the soil as microbes break them down over weeks.\n\nReasoning: Potted plants deplete nitrogen faster than they can absorb it; low N causes yellow leaves and stunted growth since the plant cannot produce chlorophyll rapidly.",
      "rubric": "- Identifies Nitrogen (N) or equivalent concept for leaf/stunting symptoms accurately.\n- Describes a natural organic source (e.g., compost/manure/mushroom substrate).",
      "skill": "apply"
    },
    {
      "prompt": "Imagine you want to boost the root growth of your container herbs during this heavy nitrogen application period without disrupting their current health.\n\nExplain how Potassium affects plant structure and list one specific organic amendment that is high in Potassium but low in Nitrogen, which would safely adjust your soil's balance.",
      "answer": "Potassium (K) strengthens cell walls and improves water uptake stress tolerance. Wood ash or kelp extract are good sources of K with lower N.\n\nReasoning: Adding more nitrogen now might cause lush top growth at the expense of roots, while potassium supports root development specifically without triggering excessive leafy growth.",
      "rubric": "- Accurately describes Potassium's role in cell structure and water stress tolerance.\n- Names a K-rich organic amendment low in N (e.g., wood ash/kelp).",
      "skill": "explain"
    },
    {
      "prompt": "You notice your tomato plants are getting large, soft leaves that attract aphids easily, while the soil test suggested phosphorus was adequate but nitrogen is still slightly depleted.\n\nCritique this thought process: \"Since it's summer and Nitrates stimulate leaf growth rapidly to support fruit production before fall, I should increase my nitrogen application rate by 50% now.\" How would you correct the plan considering typical nutrient interaction risks in confined spaces?",
      "answer": "Increasing fertilizer rates blindly without testing soil pH or specific crop needs can cause burn. Over-fertilizing with Nitrogen leads to excessive foliage (which invites pests) and dilutes essential nutrients like Potassium.\n\nCorrection: Focus on balanced feeding using slow-release organics rather than high-nitrogen concentrates.",
      "rubric": "- Identifies the risk of over-application causing leafy growth without fruit yield or pest attraction.\n- Proposes a shift to balanced/slow-release organic methods instead of concentrated N spikes.",
      "skill": "critique"
    }
  ],
  "note": null,
  "intervention": null
}

