    {
      "prompt": "Using standard electrode potentials, explain why lithium is more likely to act as a reducing agent than calcium in single replacement reactions.",
      "answer": "Lithium has a more negative standard reduction potential than calcium (approx -3.04V vs -2.87V), indicating it holds electrons less tightly and loses them more readily, making it a stronger electron donor or reducing agent.",
      "rubric": "- Correctly associates lower (more negative) potentials with greater tendency to lose electrons\n- Explains the link between electron loss potential and acting as a reducing agent",
      "skill": "apply"
    }
  ],
  "note": null,
